## Plan Summary

**Only one file changes:** `common/chat.cpp`

### Architecture insight

The codebase has two dispatch paths. The modern **Jinja/specialized path** in `common/chat.cpp` uses `common_chat_try_specialized_template` — a chain of template-source pattern checks that route to dedicated C++ handlers. This is where the new handler belongs. The legacy enum-based path (`src/llama-chat.h` / `src/llama-chat.cpp`) is untouched, satisfying "do not modify the header file."

---

### Step 1 — New handler function (insert just before `common_chat_try_specialized_template`, ~line 1633)

```cpp
// Mistral Instruct v0.3 - simple [INST]/[/INST] format, system prepended to first user turn,
// </s> after assistant turns, no [SYSTEM_PROMPT] / [AVAILABLE_TOOLS] / <<SYS>>.
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;
    data.prompt = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY;
    return data;
}
```

`common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl` renders the Jinja template (which already encodes the system-prepend logic). `COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY` is correct because this format has no tools, no reasoning, no PEG parsing.

